@node Three "HNet V1.0: 3-Wire cable"

@{b}3-Wire serial cable (nullmodem)@{ub}

A 3-Wire serial cable could be used at low speeds, but a @{"7-Wire" link Seven} cable is
recommended, especially at speeds over 19200.

If you want to use a Three-Wire cable anyway, this is the way to make one:

What you need:

A cable with 3 wires.
Two D-SUB type connectors (25-pin, female).

How to connect:

COMPUTER 1:                           COMPUTER 2:
~~~~~~~~~~~                           ~~~~~~~~~~~
TXD 2---------------\ /---------------------2 TXD
                     X
RXD 3---------------/ \---------------------3 RXD

GND 7---------------------------------------7 GND

(here)                                    (there)

Explanation:

Connect pin 2 (here) to pin 3 (there), pin 3 (here) to pin 2 (here) and
pin 7 (here) straight through to pin 7 (there).

The pin numbers are usually printed on the connectors.

To use this wire you must set "3-Wire" mode in the @{"preferences" link Prefs} editor.

@endnode

@node Seven "HNet V1.0: 7-Wire cable"

@{b}7-Wire serial cable (nullmodem)@{ub}

This cable is done the same way as the @{"3-Wire" link Three} cable, but with 4
additional wires.

How to connect:

COMPUTER 1:                           COMPUTER 2:
~~~~~~~~~~~                           ~~~~~~~~~~~
TXD 2---------------\ /---------------------2 TXD
                     X
RXD 3---------------/ \---------------------3 RXD

RTS 4---------------\ /---------------------4 RTS
                     X
CTS 5---------------/ \---------------------5 CTS

DSR 6---------------\ /---------------------6 DSR
                     X
DTR 20--------------/ \--------------------20 DTR

GND 7---------------------------------------7 GND

If you don't understand, this then ask @{"me" link I}.

If you want HNet to take advantage of the extra wires, you must set the "7-Wire"
mode in the @{"preferences" link Prefs} program.

@endnode

@node Prefs "HNet V1.0: Settings"

@{b}Settings editor@{ub}

In the current release (1.0 beta) there is no settings editor.

The program uses these settings:

7-Wire mode
64000 baud
8 data bits
No stopbits
No parity

@endnode
